Le mer 10/09/2003 � 23:23, Alex Jacobson a �crit :
&gt; Exactly what purpose does this spec serve that is not already served by 
&gt; HEAD, 405, 413,414, and 415?

First, you need an uri on which to perform your HEAD. Therefore you need
at least an uri list.

&gt; HEAD gives you the content-type which implies both the allowed POSTable 
&gt; types and the allowed query strings.

Suppose that the default content-type is html, to be complient with
browsers (like IE) that ask for */* (even if the purpose of your service
is to be queried by a specific client dealing with xml).
Therefore, the submission method is an html form, and thus the
content-type is www-url-encoded. How do you then specify the names and
the types of the form&#39;s fields ?

&gt; If the server does not support all the content-types, entities, and query 
&gt; strings implied by the content-type of the resource identified by the 
&gt; target URI, it can return the above status codes.  If the content-type of 
&gt; the target resource does not sufficiently constrain the client, choose a 
&gt; more-specific content-type.
&gt; 
&gt; The semantic web needs is better documentation of content-types.  It does 
&gt; not need better documentation of the capabilities of particular URIs.
